SIMPLE: prodigal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prodigal
<hw>Prod"i*gal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prodigus</ets>, from <ets>prodigere</ets> to drive forth, to
squander away; <ets>pro</ets> forward, forth + <ets>agere</ets> to
drive; cf. F. <ets>prodigue</ets>. See <er>Agent</er>. ]</ety>
<def>Given to extravagant expenditure; expending money or other things
without necessity; recklessly or viciously profuse; lavish; wasteful;
not frugal or economical; <as>as, a <ex>prodigal</ex> man; the
<ex>prodigal</ex> son; <ex>prodigal</ex> giving; <ex>prodigal</ex>
expenses.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In fighting fields [patriots] were <qex>prodigal</qex> of
blood.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Profuse; lavish; extravagant; squandering;
wasteful. See <er>Profuse</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prodigal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prodigal
<hw>Prod"i*gal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who expends money
extravagantly, viciously, or without necessity; one that is profuse or
lavish in any expenditure; a waster; a spendthrift.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Noble
<xex>prodigals</xex> of life.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Trench.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prodigality</ent>⟦br⟧
